SIMPLE: overgrow
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overgrow
<hw>O`ver*grow"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Overgrew</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Overgrown</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Overgrowing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To grow over; to cover with growth or herbage, esp.
that which is rank; <as>as, dandelions have <ex>overgrown</ex> the
lawn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>The green . . . is rough and <qex>overgrown</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To grow beyond; to rise above; hence, to overcome;
to oppress.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Mortimer.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>O'ergrown</xex> with labor.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Beau. &
Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>[Usually in the past participle.]</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overgrow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overgrow
<hw>O`ver*grow"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow beyond the fit or
natural size; to grow too large; <as>as, a huge, <ex>overgrown</ex>
ox</as>.</def> <rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>overgrown</ent>⟦br⟧
